snippet.textDisplay: Hi I just wanted to say, that H&M Conscious is just marketing and not that sustainable at all. You can't make actually sustainable and ethical (!) clothes for that price, and when buying the clothes, you are still supporting a fast fashion company as a whole. This is not aimed to be against you girls in particular, but it's important to note, because it's easy to fall for greenwashing, when they've given it a sustainable sounding name and made the tags green.
snippet.textOriginal: Hi I just wanted to say, that H&M Conscious is just marketing and not that sustainable at all. snippet.textDisplay:
H&M IS NOT SUSTAINABLE IN ANY RESPECT. Please be aware that many companies are aware of the trend that people want things that are more eco friendly but instead of investing the time and money to make things that are truly eco friendly/sustainable they just say a few things that sound good to make it seem like the things they’re making are sustainable but if you really look into it they’re not. This is called green washing. Just type that term into google and you can learn all about it. I know the average consumer would have no way of knowing these things without someone telling them so as a textile engineer that’s educated in this, I like to try spread awareness. A ytber called Sarah Hawkinson has a few good videos explaining stuff like this, I’d recommend giving a watch. Not hating on the video btw, just trying to inform!
Love you guys

snippet.textDisplay:
HM Conscious Line is really just greewashing. Stick to brands that are transparent about their production process and supply chain. Like seriously, try googling HM Concious line‘s actual production circumstances (like actual stats, infos etc) and the fabrics they use (any kind of synthetic fabric is not sustainable, bc they‘re made out of crude oils, or sometimes like rainforest wood and they‘re nearly impossible to recycle. on that note, HM hasnt given me much reason to not believe thag their Recycling programm is not a total scam). When companies use all these green buzzwords and have pretty websites but then no actual figured or transparency, that‘s greenwashing!
Also be mindful of the fact that the pricing at reformation is justified. sustainable and fair production, that doesn‘t rely on modern day slavery is going to be expensive. So that just might mean that we all have to learn and live with shopping less, period.

Don't buy it, you'll fall in love with it and then you'll be disappointed when it falls apart.

snippet.textDisplay:
H&M as a brand isn't sustainable. But their conscious line does use recycled materials. It should be sustainable to live sustainably, meaning that a lot of us are still gonna buy clothes and love fashion. I myself have sometimes bought an item that was from a fast fashion brand because I couldn't find it anywhere else. Sustainability is also about how long an item last in your wardrobe. If you know you'll wear it for years to come, then that's ok. Luckily H&M quality does allow for that, I have items from H&M I bought 7 years ago which are still in perfect condition.
And when that has been said, not everyone can afford the sustainable brands and if you're just looking for something you often change out anyway, like underwear or socks, let's just agree it's better to buy products that at least have some recycled materials in them than none. Just remember if you do go to H&M conscious for sustainable reasons, look at what percentage of recycled materials the item is made from, because if you can afford buying from a different place, then that might be a better option for you.
